{{California area codes image map|213}} '''Area codes 213 and 323''' are [[California]] [[telephone]] [[area code]]s in the [[North American Numbering Plan]]. They contain, roughly, the area of central [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]]. 213/323 also includes several gateway cities of the region, including [[Bell, California|Bell]] and [[Huntington Park, California|Huntington Park]]. Before being reunited in an overlay in 2017, they had been separate area codes since 1998, with 213 containing downtown Los Angeles and its immediately adjoining neighborhoods, with 323 containing the rest of the area.
==History== ===1998–2017: Separate areas=== Area code 213 was one of the three original area codes assigned to California in 1947. It initially covered the southern third of the state from the [[Central Coast (California)|Central Coast]] to the [[United States-Mexico border|Mexican border]]. The numbering plan area was extended to the north in 1950, requiring the southern portion of the [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]], including [[Bakersfield]], to change over from [[area code 415]].{{Citation needed|date = June 2016}}
As a result of southern California's rapid expansion during the second half of the 20th century, 213 has been split on numerous occasions. The first area split became necessary in 1951, when most of the southern and eastern portion, including [[Orange County, California|Orange County]] and [[San Diego]], was assigned [[area code 714]]. In 1957, 213 was restricted to [[Los Angeles County]], with most of the old 213's northern and western portion becoming [[area code 805]]. In 1984, the [[San Fernando Valley]] and the [[San Gabriel Valley]] became [[area code 818]], thus making Los Angeles one of the first major cities in the US to be split between two area codes (New York City was split between [[area code 212|212]] and [[area code 718|718]] the same year). In 1991, [[Westside (Los Angeles County)|West Los Angeles]] and the [[South Bay, Los Angeles|South Bay]] became [[area code 310]].
The 323 area code was created in 1998 as yet another split of 213.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://docs.cpuc.ca.gov/PublishedDocs/Published/G000/M165/K075/165075193.PDF|title=CPUC Provides For More Phone Numbers in 323 Area Code|last=Prosper|first=Terry|date=July 14, 2016|website=[[California Public Utilities Commission]] website|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=August 24, 2017}}</ref> When 213 was divided, it kept Los Angeles exchanges 1, 7 and 10, while exchanges 2 through 6, 8, 9, and 11 through 14 went to 323. This split made 213 one of the smallest area codes in the nation, covering only [[Downtown Los Angeles]] and its immediately adjoining neighborhoods, such as [[Chinatown, Los Angeles, California|Chinatown]]. Completely surrounding 213, 323 covered most of the remainder of central Los Angeles, including Hollywood, as well as several neighboring cities, including [[Bell, California|Bell]], [[Huntington Park, California|Huntington Park]] and [[Montebello, California|Montebello]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cpuc.ca.gov/general.aspx?id=1163|title=323 Area Code|last=|first=|authorlink=|date=|website=[[California Public Utilities Commission]] website|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=August 24, 2017}}</ref>
===Since 2017: Overlay codes=== Despite Southern California's continued rapid growth and the proliferation of cell phones and pagers, 213 was not projected to exhaust until 2050. In contrast, 323 was projected to exhaust in 2017.<ref name=":1" /> Since 213 still had an abundance of numbers available, and rather than add yet another area code to California's 30+ area codes already in service, the [[California Public Utilities Commission]] approved a plan that "erased" the 213-323 boundary, converting them into [[overlay plan|overlay]] area codes for all of central Los Angeles. Since this change went into full effect on July 8, 2017, telephone companies have been able to assign any available 213 numbers in the former 323 area and vice versa, and customers with 213 or 323 phone numbers have been required to dial the area code even to call other 213 or 323 numbers (10/11-digit dialing), even for a number next door.<ref>[http://www.nanpa.com/pdf/NRUF/April_2015_NPA_Exhaust_Projections.pdf Nanpa.com]</ref><ref>http://docs.cpuc.ca.gov/PublishedDocs/Efile/G000/M156/K071/156071980.PDF</ref> This change returned 213 to some areas that had used it for more than half a century prior to 1998.<ref name=":0" />
==In popular culture== An American hip-hop [[supergroup (music)|supergroup]] from [[Long Beach, California]] consisting of [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Warren G]], and [[Nate Dogg]] was called [[213 (group)|213]], based on the area code.
Area code 213 is referenced in [[Warren G]] and [[Nate Dogg]]'s song "[[Regulate (song)|Regulate]]", [[Dr. Dre]]'s "[[Still D.R.E.]]", the [[Electric Six]] song "I'm the Bomb", [[LL Cool J]]'s song "Going Back to Cali", [[Whitney Houston]]'s song "[[It's Not Right but It's Okay]]", and [[Eminem]]'s "[[Shake That]]". It is also referenced in "Area Codes" by Ludacris featuring Nate Dogg.
The [[Los Angeles Clippers]] mascot, Chuck the [[California condor|Condor]], has the jersey number 213.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/clippers/news/la-clippers-new-mascot-chuck-20000-chuck-taylor-giveaway LA Clippers Introduce New MascottXX Chuck]</ref>
