{{coord|40.704648|N|74.012568|W|display=title}} [[File:Marketfield Street.jpg|thumb|right|325px|Marketfield Street]]
'''Marketfield Street''' is a short one-way, one-block-long [[alley|alleyway]] in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]. The street begins as a southern branch of Beaver Street, then veers east and north, ending at [[Broad Street (Manhattan)|Broad Street]]. Alternative past names include Exchange Street, Field Street, Fieldmarket Street, Oblique Road, and Petticoat Lane.<ref name=fny>{{cite web | url=http://forgotten-ny.com/1999/05/the-alleys-of-lower-manhattan-how-did-mill-lane-marketfield-strret-and-theatre-alley-get-their-names/ | title=The Alleys of Lower Manhattan | work=[[Forgotten NY]] | date=May 1999 | accessdate=21 April 2015 | author=Walsh, Kevin}}</ref>
The name Marketfield Street is a translation from the Dutch.<ref> {{cite naming|pages=28}}</ref><ref>{{cite streetbook}}, p.75</ref> The street originally ran to the Dutch livestock market, ''Marcktveldt'', located near where [[Battery Park]] is now, which was then outside the walls of the city.<ref name=fny/><ref>Burrows & Wallace, p.36</ref> The market operated from 1638 to 1647. In 1641, the [[Governor-General]] of [[New Netherland]], [[Willem Kieft]], opened the colony's first cattle market there.<ref name=fny /><ref>{{cite book|author=Valentine, David T.| title = History of the City of New York | location = New York City | publisher = G. P. Putnam & Company | year = 1853}}</ref>
By 1680, mainly poor people were living on Marketfield Street.<ref>Burrows & Wallace, p.88</ref> In 1688, the city's first French Huguenot church was built there.<ref> {{cite book | author = Griffiths, William Elliot | title = The Story of the Walloons: at Home in Lands of Exile and in America|year=1923|pages=205, 340|publisher=Houghton}}</ref><ref>Burrows & Wallace, p.95</ref>
In September 1776, Marketfield Street was part of the area devastated by the [[Great Fire of New York (1776)|Great Fire of New York]], which engulfed the southwestern tip of Manhattan.<ref>Burrows & Wallace, p.241</ref> In 1821, a [[hurricane]] hit the [[East Coast (United States)|East Coast]], destroying the street's dock.<ref> {{cite book | author = Ludlum, David M. | title = Early American Hurricanes, 1492-1870 | location = Boston | publisher = American Meteorological Society | year = 1963 | pages = 85, 212}} </ref> In 1821, Marketfield Street, which overlooked the [[Hudson River]], had a single name throughout its length,<ref> {{cite book | chapter= 8 | title = Laws of the State of New York | location = Albany | publisher = E. Croswell | year = 1830 | pages = 8}}</ref> but by the 1830s, the street was renamed "Battery Place" from [[Bowling Green (New York City)|Bowling Green]] to the Hudson River.<ref name=fny/> The 1882 construction of the New York City Produce Exchange demolished the block of the street that contained the French church.<ref name=fny/>
In the 20th century, 70 Broad Street, between Marketfield and Beaver Street, became the headquarters of the [[American Bank Note Company]].<ref>Burrows & Wallace, pp.45, 133</ref>
