{{multiple issues|{{more footnotes|date=November 2014}} {{POV|date=July 2013}}}} {{Infobox person | name = Niall McGarry | image = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Castlebar]], [[County Mayo]] | death_date = | death_plate = | residence = [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] | nationality = [[Irish people|Irish]] | education = [[St. Gerald's College]] | occupation = | spouse = | years_active = 2014–present | children = | credits = | website = {{URL|https://www.joe.ie/}} }} '''Niall McGarry''' is an entrepreneur and the owner and founder of [[Joe (website)|Joe.ie]] and [[Her.ie]], male and female-focused websites in [[Ireland]]. Both websites fall under the banner of Maximum Media, the umbrella company founded by McGarry, who owns and runs both sites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/joeie-boss-mcgarry-plots-20m-move-on-uk-market-31283349.html|title=JOE.ie boss McGarry plots €20m move on UK market|work=[[Irish Independent]]|accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/business/personal-finance/me-my-money-niall-mcgarry-founder-of-maximum-media-1.2275256|title=Me & My Money: Niall McGarry, founder of Maximum Media|date=7 July 2015|work=[[The Irish Times]]|accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/business/media-and-marketing/maximum-media-hires-15-people-for-uk-expansion-1.2149098|title=Maximum Media hires 15 people for UK expansion|date=23 March 2015|work=[[The Irish Times]]|accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/ireland/article1638668.ece|title=Tackling sales - The Sunday Times|publisher=[[The Sunday Times]]|accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.betaboston.com/news/2014/11/12/gender-bias-web-summit/|title=Gender Issues Arise at Dublin's Web Summit - BetaBoston|publisher=[[The Boston Globe#BetaBoston|BetaBoston]]|accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref>
McGarry attended [[St. Gerald's College]] in Castlebar, [[County Mayo|Mayo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/finance/2007/1221/1197997125464.html|title=Making an impact on advertising|date=21 December 2007|work=The Irish Times|accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref> He then studied at [[Limerick Institute of Technology]] with rugby union player [[Jerry Flannery]] who owns 18 percent of Maximum Media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/jerry-flannery-munster-still-have-x-factor-and-are-ready-for-clermont-challenge-1.2027542|title=Jerry Flannery: Munster still have X factor and are ready for Clermont challenge|date=6 December 2014|work=The Irish Times|accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref> After graduating in 2002 with a degree in [[Marketing Management]], McGarry worked for just over a year in advertising sales for a newspaper in [[Galway City]]. There, he established Impact Media in 2003. The company grew and represented clients including [[Supermacs]], [[Eircom]] and [[Radisson Hotels]]. Having grown the company to a 20-strong workforce, McGarry sold this business to [[Cork (city)|Cork]] company H+A Marketing+PR in 2011. McGarry originally created JOE.ie in 2010, providing an online outlet for Irish males with an interest in areas like sport, tech, entertainment, motors and fashion. The site now{{when|date=January 2016}} attracts 3.1 million unique visitors a month. McGarry created Her.ie, a site that caters for Irish women in July 2012 and has achieved almost instant success, already attracting an audience of over 2.2 million unique visitors each month.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}
