{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}} {{Infobox person | name = Rubana Huq | native_name = রুবানা হক | native_name_lang = bn | nationality = Bangladeshi | spouse = [[Annisul Huq]] }}
'''Rubana Huq''' is a Bangladeshi businesswoman and poet.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/blogs/asia/2012/10/40066.html |title=From Milan Fashion Week to Dhaka |last=Moshiri |first=Nazanine |work=Al Jazeera |date=3 October 2012 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324112232/http://www.aljazeera.com/blogs/asia/2012/10/40066.html |archivedate=24 March 2016 |accessdate=18 December 2016 }}</ref> She is a managing director of Mohammadi Group.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/158054/Rubana-Huq-gives-a-talk-at-AIUB |title=Rubana Huq gives a talk at AIUB |work=[[Daily Sun (Bangladesh)]] |location=Dhaka |date=11 August 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218122411/http://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/158054/Rubana-Huq-gives-a-talk-at-AIUB |archivedate=18 December 2016 |accessdate=18 December 2016 }}</ref> The Group began with exporting readymade garments and then diversified into software, digital distribution, real estate, power generation and the group’s latest are has been the launch of a television channel called Nagorik. Huq was featured in [[BBC 100 Women]] in 2013 and 2014.<ref name="dhakatribune">{{cite news |last=Samira Sadeque |first=Syeda |url=http://archive.dhakatribune.com/feature/2014/mar/08/rubana-huq-emblem-empathy |title=Rubana Huq: Emblem of empathy |work=[[Dhaka Tribune]] |location=Dhaka |date=8 March 2014 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218040841/http://archive.dhakatribune.com/feature/2014/mar/08/rubana-huq-emblem-empathy |archivedate=18 December 2016 |accessdate=18 December 2016 }}</ref>
==Career== Huq served as the CEO of [[TV Southasia]] from 2006 to 2010.<ref name="berkeley">{{cite web |url=http://events.berkeley.edu/index.php/calendar/sn/sseas.html?event_ID=97215&ovrrdr=1 |title=Rubana Huq / Price and Progress: Beyond Rana Plaza in Bangladesh |work=Department of South & Southeast Asian Studies, University of California, Berkeley |publisher=Regents of the University of California |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218042649/http://events.berkeley.edu/index.php/calendar/sn/sseas.html?event_ID=97215&ovrrdr=1 |archivedate=18 December 2016 |accessdate=18 December 2016 }}</ref>
Huq won the [[SAARC Literary Award]] for her poems in 2006.<ref name="berkeley"/> She wrote a book of poems ''Time of My Life''.
Huq is a member of board of trustees in [[Asian University for Women]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.auw.edu.bd/about/governance/auw-board-of-trustees/ |title=AUW Board of Trustees |work=[[Asian University for Women]] |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160522104759/http://www.auw.edu.bd/about/governance/auw-board-of-trustees/ |archivedate=22 May 2016 |accessdate=18 December 2016 }}</ref>
On 13 August 2018, Huq was awarded PhD from [[Jadavpur University]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aiub.edu/talk-show-on-women-entrepreneurs-of-bangladesh-status-problems-prospects-2 |title=Talk Show on 'Women Entrepreneurs of Bangladesh: Status, Problems & Prospects’ |work=[[American International University-Bangladesh]] |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218123851/http://www.aiub.edu/talk-show-on-women-entrepreneurs-of-bangladesh-status-problems-prospects-2 |archivedate=18 December 2016 |accessdate=18 December 2016 }}</ref>
==Personal life== Huq was married to [[Annisul Huq]], the late mayor of [[Dhaka North City Corporation]]. Together they have three children.
