{{Infobox organization |name = The 2.0 Adoption Council |image = |image_border = |size = |alt = |caption = |map = |msize = |malt = |mcaption = |abbreviation = 2.0AC |motto = ''Engage. Evangelize. Empower.'' |formation = June 2009 |extinction = |type = |status = |purpose = |headquarters = Virtual Space |location = |coords = |region_served = Worldwide |membership = Corporate enterprise collaboration leaders |language = |leader_title = Leader |leader_name = [https://twitter.com/itsinsider Susan Scrupski] |main_organ = |parent_organization = [http://www.dachisgroup.com Dachis Group] |affiliations = |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |budget = |website = [http://www.20adoptioncouncil.com 20AdoptionCouncil.com] |remarks = }}
'''The 2.0 Adoption Council''' is a free-to-join [[peer group]] of corporate leaders focused on the adoption and utilization of [[Enterprise 2.0]] collaboration tools. The organization's stated objective is "''to gain practical insights on innovative business practices using 2.0 tools, processes and strategies for cost efficiencies in tough economic times, as well as leveraging agility for [[competitive advantage]]''".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.20adoptioncouncil.com/?page_id=4 |title=The 2.0 Adoption Council &raquo; About Us |accessdate=2011-02-15 }}</ref> The group was founded in 2009 by [[industry analyst]] Susan Scrupski.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fastcompany.com/article/susan-scrupski-20-adoption-council |title=Susan Scrupski, founder and CEO of the 2.0 Adoption Council (Most Influential Women in Technology 2010: The Evangelists) |accessdate=2011-02-16 }}</ref> The Council began as an independent entity and was acquired in 2010 by the [[Enterprise 2.0]] consultancy [https://web.archive.org/web/20110217034349/http://www.dachisgroup.com/ Dachis Group].
== Industry Impact == The Council produces original research in the form of white papers and regular surveys of its members. This research is used by industry analysts to identify and interpret technology trends.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zdnet.com/blog/hinchcliffe/as-collaboration-goes-social-where-will-it-thrive/1497 |title=As collaboration goes social, where will it thrive? |accessdate=2011-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://andrewmcafee.org/2010/04/whats_going_on/ |title=What's Going On |accessdate=2011-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pcworld.com/article/198622/enterprises_slowly_adopting_social_tech.html |title=Enterprises Slowly Adopting Social Tech |accessdate=2011-02-16}}</ref> Some influential Council members have taken professional positions at enterprise collaboration vendors (ex: [[Yammer]], [http://www.moxiesoft.com/ Moxie]), which necessitated their departure from the Council due to its ongoing "no vendors allowed" policy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.readwriteweb.com/enterprise/2011/01/thoughts-on-paul-greenbergs-cr.php |title=Thoughts on Paul Greenberg's CRM 2011 Watchlist |accessdate=2011-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.informationweek.com/news/global-cio/recruiting/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=229215134 |title=Yammer Beefs Up Executive Suite |accessdate=2011-02-15}}</ref>
The Council is unique in its position as a no-fee peer group focused on [[Enterprise 2.0]]. In recent years, council members have been heavily involved in the [http://www.e2conf.com Enterprise 2.0 Conference] series, leading workshops and panel discussions on enterprise collaboration and other topics of interest to practitioners.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cio.com/article/596596/Enterprises_Slowly_Adopting_Social_Tech |title=Enterprises Slowly Adopting Social Tech |accessdate=2011-02-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zdnet.com/blog/collaboration/the-enterprise-20-value-propositions-agenda/1034 |title=The Enterprise 2.0 Value Propositions Agenda |accessdate=2011-02-16}}</ref> The Council has publicly presented an ''Internal Evangelist of the Year'' award yearly to a member nominated by his or her coworkers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cflanagan.wordpress.com/2009/11/08/enterprise-2-0-internal-evangelist-of-the-year/ |title=Internal Evangelist of the Year 2009 |accessdate=2011-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lbenitez.com/2010/12/ibm-luis-suarez-awarded-internal-social.html |title=IBM's Luis Suarez Awarded Internal Social Software Evangelist of the Year |accessdate=2011-02-15}}</ref>
